### Read In and Store Data

# Empty lists to store the files I'll be working with
im_list_vehicles = []
im_list_non_vehicles = []

# Read in vehicle files and add them to the list
for file in glob.glob('data/vehicles/*'):
    
    im = mpimg.imread(file)
    
    im_list_vehicles.append((im,1)) # vehicles will have the class label 1
    
# Do the same for non-vehicles    
for file in glob.glob('data/non-vehicles/*'):
    
    im = mpimg.imread(file)
    
    im_list_non_vehicles.append((im,0)) # non-vehicles will have the class label 0
    
# Make sure they read in properly by looking at the size of the lists    
print('Number of Non-Vehicle Images: ', len(im_list_non_vehicles)) 
print()
print('Number of Vehicle Images: ', len(im_list_vehicles))

### Prepare the Data

# This function should take in an RGB image and returns a new, standardized version with standard pixel dimensions
def standardize_input(image):
    image_crop = np.copy(image)
    row_crop = 7
    col_crop = 8
    image_crop = image[row_crop:-row_crop, col_crop:-col_crop, :]
    ## TODO: Resize image and pre-process so that all "standard" images are the same size
    standard_im = cv2.resize(image_crop, (32, 32))
    return standard_im

# This function standardizes images within lists of images
def standardize(image_list):
    
    # Empty image data array
    standard_list = []

    # Iterate through all the image-label pairs
    for item in image_list:
        image = item[0]
        label = item[1]

        # Standardize the image using the previously made standardize_input function
        standardized_im = standardize_input(image)

        # Append the image, and it's one hot encoded label to the full, processed list of image data 
        standard_list.append((standardized_im, label))
        
    return standard_list

# Create a standardized image list
std_im_list = standardize(im_list)

### Prepare the data

# Shuffle the image and label data set
random.shuffle(std_im_list)

# Then split it up into separate lists: images and labels
train_images = [] # images list
train_labels = [] # labels list ---> both of these are in the correct index oder to match up later

# Add images and labels from our full list to our images and labels lists
for im in std_im_list:
    train_images.append(im[0])
    train_labels.append(im[1])

# Check to see that labels got shuffled and are correct (if yes, then they will be a mix of labels 
# rather than 10 of the same ones)
print('Image Labels: ', train_labels[0:10])

### Graphing Functions for Predictions

# For plotting an image
def plot_image(i, predictions_array, true_label, img):
    true_label, img = true_label[i], img[i]
    plt.grid(False)
    plt.xticks([])
    plt.yticks([])

    plt.imshow(img, cmap=plt.cm.binary)

    predicted_label = np.argmax(predictions_array)
    
    if predicted_label == true_label:
        color = 'blue'
    else:
        color = 'red'

    plt.xlabel("{} {:2.0f}% ({})".format(class_names[predicted_label],
                                100*np.max(predictions_array),
                                class_names[true_label]),
                                color=color)


# For printing various images as subplots
def plot_image_subplots(i, predictions_array, true_label, img):
    
    true_label, img = true_label[i], img[i]
    
    # print(true_label)
    
    plt.subplot(6,2,i+1) # add this from earlier --> remove i+1
    plt.grid(False)
    plt.xticks([])
    plt.yticks([])
    plt.tight_layout() # sets the correct spacing between plots/images

    plt.imshow(img, cmap=plt.cm.binary)
    
    # print(predictions_array) ---> see what's going on for debugging purposes

    predicted_label = np.argmax(predictions_array) # added [i] to the predictions_array part of this because 
    # it wouldn't work without it ---> otherwise gives you a result like 308 that is outside the class_names range
    
    # print(predicted_label)
    
    if predicted_label == true_label:
        color = 'blue'
      
    else:
        color = 'red'

    plt.xlabel("{} {:2.0f}% ({})".format(class_names[predicted_label],
                                         100*np.max(predictions_array),
                                         class_names[true_label]),color=color)

# For looking at prediction values    
def plot_value_array(i, predictions_array, true_label):
    
    true_label = true_label[i]
    
    plt.grid(False)
    plt.xticks(range(len(predictions_array))) # changed the range here as well to help with x-axis mapping
    plt.yticks([])
    
    # changed the range to the length of the predictions array so that it will correctly map the images
    thisplot = plt.bar(range(len(predictions_array)), predictions_array, color="#777777")
    
    plt.ylim([0, 1])
    predicted_label = np.argmax(predictions_array)

    thisplot[predicted_label].set_color('red')
    thisplot[true_label].set_color('blue')
    
    plt.title('Class Probabilities for Image #' + str(i+1),
             fontsize='small',
             style='italic',
             loc='left')
    plt.xlabel('Class Label')
    plt.ylabel('Probability')

### Building, Training, and Testing the Model: Random Forest

# Create an empty output list to map to a Pandas dataframe
output = []

for nestimator in [10,50,100,300,500]:
    
    clf = RFC(n_estimators=nestimator, max_depth=16, min_samples_leaf=10, random_state=123)
    clf.fit(forest_x_train, y_train)
    train_acc = accuracy_score(y_train, clf.predict(forest_x_train))
    test_acc = accuracy_score(y_test, clf.predict(forest_x_test)) 
    # ---> use this^^^ once we've split the dataset into train and testing
    output.append({'n_estimator':nestimator, 'Training Accuracy':train_acc, 'Testing Accuracy':test_acc}) 
    # , 'Testing Accuracy':test_acc ---> add this^^^ once you have split the data up into a training and test set
    
    
output = pd.DataFrame(output)

output # around 300 estimators seems to work just fine

### Testing the Model: Random Forest

# Seems like 100-300 estimators will do just fine. Let's try 250. Testing reaches accuracy well over 96%.
clf = RFC(n_estimators=250, max_depth=16, min_samples_leaf=10, random_state=123)
clf.fit(forest_x_train,y_train)
train_acc = accuracy_score(y_train, clf.predict(forest_x_train))
clf.fit(forest_x_test,y_test)
test_acc = accuracy_score(y_test, clf.predict(forest_x_test))

print('Training Accuracy with 250 Estimators: ', train_acc)
print()
print('Testing Accuracy with 250 Estimators: ', test_acc)
